<li id="cite_note-17"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFEliason1999" class="citation journal cs1">Eliason, Eric A. (1999). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/byusq/vol38/iss1/12/">"Toward the Folkloristic Study of Latter-day Saint Conversion Narratives"</a>. <i>BYU Studies Quarterly</i>. <b>38</b> (1)<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">11 May</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=BYU+Studies+Quarterly&amp;rft.atitle=Toward+the+Folkloristic+Study+of+Latter-day+Saint+Conversion+Narratives&amp;rft.volume=38&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.aulast=Eliason&amp;rft.aufirst=Eric+A.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fscholarsarchive.byu.edu%2Fbyusq%2Fvol38%2Fiss1%2F12%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMormon+folklore" class="Z3988"></span> "Latter-day Saints often evaluate conversion narratives and testimonies based on an antiperformance aesthetic. Stories that seem contrived, melodramatic, self-centered, or manipulative can be deemed in violation of the principles of this genre's <i>raisons d'être</i>."</span>
